PROJECT 4: IAM Security Audit
Date: Day 7
What I built:

Conducted complete IAM security audit across all users
Downloaded and analyzed IAM credential report
Reviewed all users, groups and permissions
Implemented strong password policy (14 characters, 90 day expiry)
Reviewed all IAM roles and their last used dates
Audited custom policies for least privilege compliance
Analyzed service usage via Access Advisor for all users
Created and ran IAM Access Analyzer
Reviewed analyzer findings for external access issues
Produced complete IAM security audit report

Security controls applied:

Strong password policy enforced (14 chars, uppercase, lowercase, numbers, symbols)
Password expiration set to 90 days
Password reuse prevention set to last 5 passwords
MFA verified active on all 3 users
Least privilege verified on all custom policies
IAM Access Analyzer enabled for continuous monitoring
Access Advisor reviewed to identify unused permissions

Audit findings:

MFA Status: Enabled on all users
Password Policy: Updated to strong settings
Custom Policies: Least privilege confirmed
IAM Roles: Reviewed and documented
Access Analyzer: Active and monitoring
Unused Services: Identified via Access Advisor
External Access: No findings detected

Challenges faced and resolved:

Access Advisor location not immediately obvious
Found under individual user page in tabs section
Located successfully under Permissions tab area

Real world value:

IAM audit is the first thing every security team does when joining a new company
Access Advisor is used to identify and remove unnecessary permissions
IAM Access Analyzer is used by companies to detect unintended external access
Strong password policy is required for most compliance frameworks including SOC2 and ISO27001
This exact audit process is asked about in every cloud security interview

Key learnings:

Credential report gives instant overview of all user security status
Access Advisor shows exactly which services are used and unused
Unused permissions should always be removed — principle of least privilege
Password policy affects all IAM users in the entire account
IAM Access Analyzer continuously monitors for unintended resource sharing
Regular IAM audits are essential security hygiene in every cloud environment
Strong password policy alone is not enough — MFA is always required
